snippet.textDisplay:
Shame on the UFC for promoting this fight as competitive. It was an embarrassment to the sport. This was no different to Bellator feeding Michael Page a series of no-name losers like Dave Rickels or whatever his name is, or feeding Jake Hager a guy with a beer belly.

The fact that people thought Cerrone would land a head kick on a guy who hasn't bled in the Octagon, or even been scratched, is hilarious. The fact that people believed he would just take McGregor down at will when he legitimately held his own in a wrestling scramble against Khabib Nurmagomedov is laughable. The fact that people thought Cerrone's black belt in jiu jitsu would be a factor when Conor escaped Khabib's full mount defies logic. Cerrone had no chance coming into this fight.

Cerrone is the most overrated fighter in MMA history. He is an adrenalin junkie with no MMA IQ. He has no head movement despite that flaw being pointed out five years ago. He is a prime candidate for long-term brain damage and physical hardship because the MMA fans, media, and UFC have enabled his addiction. They should have to reflect on this with guilt for years to come.

Yes, Cerrone willingly signs up for fights, but he is an addict. You can't cheer raucously when he tips his hat and says 'I love this game' moments after he gets his nose broken by a shoulder and claim innocence. Cerrone fans are fucking enablers, they're as bad as drug dealers.

Every time he goes up against a good opponent, he doesn't show up. He was a punching bag for Nate Diaz, and crumbled against Gaethje, Masvidal, and Dos Anjos. He did absolutely nothing against Ferguson. The fact that people thought this fight would be competitive based on his wins against Mike Perry, Yancy Medeiros, Rick Story, Alexander Hernandez, and Al Iaquinta is shameful, when McGregor is by far the best boxer and arguably the best overall striker in the history of this sport. Honestly, fuck this sport, and all of its ignorant, drunk, 'Just Bleed' fans who boo grappling exchanges.

That's not to say McGregor doesn't deserve credit. Allegations about his personal life aside, he is an extraordinary athlete. The touchbutt with the dork in the park is exactly what sets him apart, because he goes above and beyond to improve. He is the best striker in the history of the sport, and his rise to the top is incredible. Cult of personality, indeed.

But what I absolutely do not agree with is the inevitable outpouring of accolades and hyperbole about McGregor that will already have begun as I'm typing this. You don't get plaudits for winning arguably the best stylistic matchup for you in the entire sport, just as McGregor wasn't criticized after losing against Khabib, who presented arguably the worst stylistic matchup in the entire sport. You just can't.

Honestly, this fight has left such a bitter taste in my mouth. Shame, shame, shame.
